none: Trattato nuovo delle cose maravigliose dell'alma citta' di Roma : ornato de molte figure, nel quale si discorre de 300. & più chiese / composto da F. Pietro Martire Felini ... ; et de tutte le antichita figurate d'essa città, già da Prospero Parisio aumentate, et hora dal sopradetto F. Pietro Martire con diligenza corrette, ampliate, e con bellissimo ordine disposte.

Pietro Martire Felini’s Trattato is often regarded as a landmark for the of the evolution of the genre. This guidebooks witnesses the progressive emergency of secular Rome as an object of interest in its own right, as equal to its ancient model. The further increased interest in the city’s monuments is showed in thematic sections, such as the section Delle Statue, an illustrated gallery of ancient and modern sculptures in Rome, or the one devoted to on obelisks recounting the interventions of Sixtus V, not their ancient history. The three day tour, the “guida romana” is preceded by the conventional chapter on the sette chiese organized by entirely new order which would be imitated until the eighteenth century. The section on Antichità is largely based on Prospero Parisio texts derived from Andrea Palladio.

Altemps Palace at Monte Cavallo (now Pallavicini- Rospigliosi) was erected on the site of the Baths of Constantine on the Quirinal Hill by Scipione Borghese Caffarelli (1577–1633), who started the construction of the palace during the first years of the 17th century. Borghese sold it shortly afterward in 1616 to Duke Giovanni Angelo Altemps (1587–1620), who owned it until 1619.
